## Findings

- IDS complements firewalls by detecting malicious activity inside networks.
- Signature-based IDS is efficient but limited to known threats.
- Anomaly-based IDS detects zero-day attacks but requires fine-tuning.
- Snort provides flexible detection through custom rules and PCAP analysis.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Deploy IDS alongside firewalls for layered defense.
- Regularly update signature databases.
- Fine-tune anomaly detection to reduce false positives.
- Use hybrid IDS for balanced detection.
- Log and analyze traffic for forensic investigations.

## Conclusion

- IDS is critical for detecting threats that bypass firewalls.
- Different deployment and detection modes serve different needs.
- Snort is a powerful open-source IDS with customizable rules.
- IDS alerts guide administrators in responding to suspicious activity.
- Practical labs strengthen understanding of IDS operations.
